<font color="#FF0000">TO DAWN FROM YOUR OTHER FAMILY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 27  0:16:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Dawn, you sound like my daughters that I have had the pleasure of enjoying because others died in my place, because others did not come home, yet I know others did make it home because I was there. <br><br>
Reading what you have written makes me proud, proud of you and proud of your dad. I know he would have enjoyed your sense of pride and the honor you give him by accepting those that served in Vietnam.<br><br>
Michael Murphy was a good friend of mine. He stepped to get around me while a sniper was taking aim at a machine gunner in order to knock out the machine gun I was carrying. Murphy was killed with the bullet with my name on it.<br>
A week before he had received a picture of his brand new baby girl that he never got to see except in that picture. He had showed all of us his daughters picture, just the night before,  He was a proud father. <br>
I'm sure your father was just as proud and would be very proud of you today. <br>
I now have five daughters and they are all very proud of their father and the service we all rendered to others in Vietnam.  <br>
I would love to meet Murphy's daughter oneday, Cris at Friends of the Vietnam Memorial, is looking and perhaps one day, I and others that knew another little girls father will have our meeting as you have had. Thank you for the posting.<br>
 <br>
Michael Murphy, 26 May 1968, Panel 66W Line 010 <br><br>
From a member of your other family, Love Cook
